panel.cor <- function(x, y, ...){
usr <- par("usr"); on.exit(par(usr))
par(usr = c(0, 1, 0, 1))
r <- round(cor(x, y), 2)
text(0.5, 0.5, r, cex = 1.75)
}

x = diff(log(varve)) # data
r = acf1(x, 1, plot=FALSE) # acf(1)
c(0) -> w -> z -> Sc -> Sz -> Szw -> para # initialize
num = length(x) # = 633
## Estimation
para[1] = (1-sqrt(1-4*(r^2)))/(2*r) # MME
niter = 12
for (j in 1:niter){
for (i in 2:num){ w[i] = x[i] - para[j]*w[i-1]
z[i] = w[i-1] - para[j]*z[i-1]
}
Sc[j] = sum(w^2)
Sz[j] = sum(z^2)
Szw[j] = sum(z*w)
para[j+1] = para[j] + Szw[j]/Sz[j]
}
## Results
cbind(iteration=1:niter-1, thetahat=para[1:niter], Sc, Sz)

for (i in -4:4){
k = i/n; wk = w+k; wpk = wp+k; wmk = wm+k
z = complex(real=0, imag=2*pi*wk)
zp = complex(real=0, imag=2*pi*wpk)
zm = complex(real=0, imag=2*pi*wmk)
d = exp(z)*(1-exp(z*n))/(1-exp(z))
dp = exp(zp)*(1-exp(zp*n))/(1-exp(zp))
dm = exp(zm)*(1-exp(zm*n))/(1-exp(zm))
D = .5*d - .25*dm*exp(pi*w/n)-.25*dp*exp(-pi*w/n)
D2 = abs(D)^2

}

APARCH Analysis of the DJIA Returns

The R package fGarch was used to fit an AR-APARCH model to the DJIA returns discussed in Example 8.2. As in the previous example, we include an AR(1) in the model to account for the conditional mean. In this case, we may think of the model as rt = mt + yt where mt is an AR(1), and yt is APARCH noise with conditional variance modeled as (8.12) with t-errors. A partial output of the analysis is given below. We do not include displays, but we show how to obtain them.
